# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: time-of-flight-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] A **laser rangefinder**, also known as a **laser telemeter** or **laser distance meter**, is a rangefinder that uses a laser beam to determine the distance to an object.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] The most common form of laser rangefinder operates on the time of flight principle by sending a laser pulse in a narrow beam towards the object and measuring the time taken by the pulse to be reflected off the target and returned to the sender.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Due to the high speed of light, this technique is not appropriate for high precision sub-millimeter measurements, where triangulation and other techniques are often used instead.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders are sometimes classified as type of handheld scannerless lidar.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] The pulse may be coded to reduce the chance that the rangefinder can be jammed.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] It is possible to use Doppler effect techniques to judge whether the object is moving towards or away from the rangefinder, and if so, how fast.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] The precision of an instrument is correlated with the rise time, divergence, and power of its laser pulse, as well as the quality of its optics and onboard digital signal processing.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] In good conditions, skilled operators using precision laser rangefinders can range a target to within a meter at distances on the order of three kilometers.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Some of the laser light might reflect off leaves or branches which are closer than the object, giving an early return and a reading which is too low.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Alternatively, over distances longer than 360 m, if the target is in proximity to the earth, it may simply vanish into a mirage, caused by temperature gradients in the air in proximity to the heated surface bending the laser light.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] where *c* is the speed of light and *t* is the amount of time for the round-trip between A and B.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] where *φ* is the phase delay made by the light traveling and *ω* is the angular frequency of optical wave.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] In this equation, *λ* is the wavelength ⁠*c*/*f*⁠; *Δφ* is the part of the phase delay that does not fulfill π (that is, *φ* modulo π); *N* is the integer number of wave half-cycles of the round-trip and Δ*N* the remaining fractional part.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Rangefinders provide an precise distance to targets located beyond the distance of point-blank shooting to snipers and artillery.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] They can also be used for military reconnaissance and engineering.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Tanks usually use LRF to correct the direct shoot solution.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Handheld military rangefinders operate at ranges of 2 km up to 25 km and are combined with binoculars or monoculars.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] When the rangefinder is equipped with a digital magnetic compass (DMC) and inclinometer it is capable of providing magnetic azimuth, inclination, and height (length) of targets.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Some rangefinders can also measure a target's speed in relation to the observer.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Some rangefinders have cable or wireless interfaces to enable them to transfer their measurement(s) data to other equipment like fire control computers.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Some models also offer the possibility to use add-on night vision modules.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Most handheld rangefinders as of this date used standard or rechargeable batteries.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] The more powerful models of rangefinders measure distance up to 40 km and are normally installed either on a tripod or directly on a vehicle, ship, jet, helicopter or gun platform.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] In the latter case the rangefinder module is integrated with on-board thermal, night vision and daytime observation equipment.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] The most advanced military rangefinders can be integrated with computers.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] To make laser rangefinders and laser-guided weapons less useful against military targets, various military arms may have developed laser-absorbing paint for their vehicles; regardless, some objects do not reflect laser light very well, and using a laser rangefinder on them is difficult.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] The first commercial laser rangefinder was the Barr & Stroud LF1, developed in association with Hughes Aircraft, which became available in 1965.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] This was then followed by the Barr & Stroud LF2, which integrated the rangefinder into a tank sight, and this was used on the Chieftain tank in 1969, the first vehicle so-equipped with such a system.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders are used extensively in 3D object recognition, 3D object modelling, and a wide variety of computer vision-related fields.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] This technology constitutes the heart of the so-called *time-of-flight* 3D scanners.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] In contrast to the military instruments, laser rangefinders offer high-precision scanning abilities, with either single-face or 360-degree scanning modes.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] A number of algorithms have been developed to merge the range data retrieved from multiple angles of a single object to produce complete 3D models with as little error as possible.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] One of the advantages offered by laser rangefinders over other methods of computer vision is in not needing to correlate features from two images in order to determine depth-information like stereoscopic methods do.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders used in computer vision applications often have depth resolutions of 0.1 mm or less.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] This can be achieved by using triangulation or refraction measurement techniques unlike to the time of flight techniques used in LIDAR.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Special laser rangefinders are used in forestry.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] These devices have anti-leaf filters and work with reflectors.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser beam reflects only from this reflector and so exact distance measurement is guaranteed.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders with anti-leaf filter are used for example for forest inventories.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders may be effectively used in various sports that require precision distance measurement, such as golf, hunting, and archery.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Some of the more popular manufacturers are Caddytalk, Opti-logic Corporation, Bushnell, Leupold, LaserTechnology, Trimble, Leica, Newcon Optik, Op.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Electronics, Nikon, Swarovski Optik and Zeiss.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Many rangefinders from Bushnell come with advanced features, such as ARC (angle range compensation), multi-distance ability, slope, JOLT (Vibrate when the target is locked), and Pin-Seeking.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] ARC can be calculated by hand using the rifleman's rule, but it's usually much easier if you let a rangefinder do it when you are out hunting.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] In golfing where time is most important, a laser rangefinder comes useful in locating distance to the flag.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] However not all features are 100% legal for golf tournament play.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Many hunters in the eastern U.S. don't need a rangefinder, although many western hunters need them, due to longer shooting distances and more open spaces.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] An important application is the use of laser rangefinder technology during the automation of stock management systems and production processes in steel industry.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders are also used in several industries like construction, renovation and real estate as alternatives to tape measures, and was first introduced by Leica Geosystems in 1993 in France.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] To measure a large object like a room with a tape measure, one would need another person to hold the tape at the far wall and a clear line straight across the room to stretch the tape.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] With a laser measuring tool, the job can be completed by one operator with just a line of sight.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Although tape measures are technically perfectly accurate, laser measuring tools are much more precise.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser measuring tools typically include the ability to produce some simple calculations, such as the area or volume of a room.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] These devices can be found in hardware stores and online marketplaces.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders can vary in price, depending on the quality and application of the product.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Military grade rangefinders need to be as accurate as possible and must also reach great distances.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] These devices can cost hundreds of thousands of dollars.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] For civilian applications, such as hunting or golf, devices are more affordable and much more readily accessible.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders are divided into four classes and several subclasses.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Laser rangefinders available to consumers are usually laser class 1 or class 2 devices and are considered relatively eye-safe.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Regardless of the safety rating, direct eye contact should always be avoided.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/laser-rangefinder] Most laser rangefinders for military use exceed the laser class 2 energy levels.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] A **rangefinder** (also **rangefinding telemeter**, depending on the context) is a device used to measure distances to remote objects.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Originally optical devices used in surveying, they soon found applications in other fields, such as photography, the military, and space travel.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] They were especially useful for finding the range of a target, such as in naval gunnery and anti-aircraft artillery.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] The word *telemeter* is derived from Ancient Greek τῆλε*(*têle*)* 'distant, far away' and μέτρον*(*métron*)* 'something used to measure'.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] The first rangefinder telemeter was invented by James Watt in 1769 and put to use in 1771 in surveying canals.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Watt called his instrument a micrometer, a term now used with a different meaning in engineering (the micrometer screw gauge).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] It consisted of two parallel hairs in the focal plane of a telescope eyepiece crossing an upright hair.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] At the point to be measured, two sliding targets on a surveyor's rod were adjusted to align with the hairs in the telescope.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] The distance to the rod could then be determined from the distance between the targets on the rod by trigonometry.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Several others have been credited with the invention of the rangefinder telemeter at one time or another.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] The Royal Society of Arts gave an award to W.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Green for its invention in 1778, even though they were made aware of Watt's priority.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] In 1778, Georg Friedrich Brander invented the coincidence rangefinder.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Two mirrors set a distance apart horizontally in a long slim box, similar to a subtense bar but located at the measuring station, and forming two images.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] This rangefinder does not require a measuring rod at the target and could perhaps be considered the first true telemeter.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] In 1790 Jesse Ramsden invented a half-image range finder.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Though Alexander Selligue is often mistakenly credited with the invention, he did invent an improved rangefinder with fixed lenses in 1821 and is responsible for coining the term.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] In 1881, the British Royal Artillery adopted the depression range finder, which had been developed by Captain H.S.S.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] It used the measurement of the angle of depression from the observer, sited on a high vantage point, to the waterline of the target vessel.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] In 1899, Carl Pulfrich at Carl Zeiss AG fabricated a practical stereoscopic rangefinder, based on a patent of Hector Alexander de Grousilliers.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] World War II-era rangefinders worked optically with two telescopes focused on the same target but a distance apart along a baseline.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] The range to the target is found by measuring the difference in bearing of the two telescopes and solving the skinny triangle.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Solutions can be obtained automatically, using tables or, rarely, manual calculation.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] The greater the distance to the target, the longer the baseline needs to be for accurate measurement.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Modern rangefinders use an electronic technology such as lasers or radar.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] A laser rangefinder, also known as a laser telemeter or laser distance meter, is a rangefinder that uses a laser beam to determine the distance to an object.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Applications include surveying, navigation, to assist focusing in photography, choosing a golf club according to distance, and correcting aim of a projectile weapon for distance.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Laser rangefinders are used in golf to measure the yardage of a particular shot but also to gauge slope and wind as well.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] There has been debate over whether they should be allowed in tournaments.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] While their use is banned on the professional level, they are becoming widely used on the amateur level.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Rangefinders may be used by users of firearms over long distances, to measure the distance to a target to allow for projectile drop.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Until the development of electronic means of measuring range during the Second World War, warships used very large optical rangefinders—with a baseline of many meters—to measure range for naval gunnery.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] In recent decades, laser rangefinders have become popular in archery, especially among bowhunters.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Rangefinders marketed for archery use will have angle-compensation features, with an internal computer calculating the horizontal distance to the target.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Bowhunters will often shoot from treestands or in steep terrain, and for relatively short shots (40 yards and under), an archer will need to aim using the horizontal distance instead of the line-of-sight distance.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Rangefinders are used for surveying in forestry.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Special devices with anti-leaf filters are used.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/rangefinder] Since the 1990s, rangefinders have been used in virtual reality systems to detect operator movements and locate objects.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A **single-photon avalanche diode** (**SPAD**), also called **Geiger-mode avalanche photodiode** (**G-APD** or **GM-APD**) is a solid-state photodetector within the same family as photodiodes and avalanche photodiodes (APDs), while also being fundamentally linked with basic diode behaviours.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In a photodiode, with a low reverse bias voltage, the leakage current changes linearly with absorption of photons, i.e. the liberation of current carriers (electrons and/or holes) due to the internal photoelectric effect.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, in a SPAD, the reverse bias is so high that a phenomenon called impact ionisation occurs which is able to cause an avalanche current to develop.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Simply, a photo-generated carrier is accelerated by the electric field in the device to a kinetic energy which is enough to overcome the ionisation energy of the bulk material, knocking electrons out of an atom.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A large avalanche of current carriers grows exponentially and can be triggered from as few as a single photon-initiated carrier.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A SPAD is able to detect single photons providing short duration trigger pulses that can be counted.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, they can also be used to obtain the time of arrival of the incident photon due to the high speed that the avalanche builds up and the device's low timing jitter.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The fundamental difference between SPADs and APDs or photodiodes, is that a SPAD is biased well above its reverse-bias breakdown voltage and has a structure that allows operation without damage or undue noise.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] While an APD is able to act as a linear amplifier, the level of impact ionisation and avalanche within the SPAD has prompted researchers to liken the device to a Geiger-counter in which output pulses indicate a trigger or "click" event.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The diode bias region that gives rise to this "click" type behaviour is therefore called the "*Geiger-mode*" region.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As with photodiodes the wavelength region in which it is most sensitive is a product of its material properties, in particular the energy bandgap within the semiconductor.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Many materials including silicon, germanium, germanium on silicon and III-V elements such as InGaAs/InP have been used to fabricate SPADs for the large variety of applications that now utilise the run-away avalanche process.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] There is much research in this topic with activity implementing SPAD-based systems in CMOS fabrication technologies, and investigation and use of III-V material combinations and Ge on Si for single-photon detection at short-wave infrared wavelengths suitable for telecommunications applications.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Since the 1970s, the applications of SPADs have increased significantly.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Recent examples of their use include LIDAR, time of flight (ToF) 3D imaging, PET scanning, single-photon experimentation within physics, fluorescence lifetime microscopy, optical communications (particularly quantum key distribution), digital night vision, and ultrahigh sensitivity cameras.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] SPADs are semiconductor devices that are based on a p–n junction that is reverse-biased at an operating voltage that exceeds the junction's breakdown voltage (Figure 1).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] "At this bias, the electric field is so high [higher than 3×105 V/cm] that a single charge carrier injected into the depletion layer can trigger a self-sustaining avalanche.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The current rises swiftly [sub-nanosecond rise-time] to a macroscopic steady level in the milliampere range.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In order to be able to detect another photon, the bias voltage must be raised again above breakdown.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Generate a standard output pulse synchronous with the avalanche build-up.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Quench the avalanche by lowering the bias down to the breakdown voltage.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Restore the photodiode to the operative level.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A semiconductor p-n junction can be biased at several operating regions depending on the applied voltage.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] For normal uni-directional diode operation, the forward biasing region and the forward voltage are used during conduction, while the reverse bias region prevents conduction.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] When operated with a low reverse bias voltage, the p-n junction can operate as a unity gain photodiode.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As the reverse bias increases, some internal gain through carrier multiplication can occur allowing the photodiode to operate as an avalanche photodiode (APD) with a stable gain and a linear response to the optical input signal.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, as the bias voltage continues to increase, the p-n junction breaks down when the electric field strength across the p-n junction reaches a critical level.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As this electric field is induced by the bias voltage over the junction it is denoted as the breakdown voltage, VBD.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A SPAD is reverse biased with an excess bias voltage, Vex, above the breakdown voltage, but below a second, higher breakdown voltage associated with the SPAD's guard ring.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The total bias (VBD+Vex) therefore exceeds the breakdown voltage to such a degree that "At this bias, the electric field is so high [higher than 3×105 V/cm] that a single charge carrier injected into the depletion layer can trigger a self-sustaining avalanche.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] If the primary carrier is photo-generated, the leading edge of the avalanche pulse marks [with picosecond time jitter] the arrival time of the detected photon".
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As the current vs voltage (I-V) characteristic of a p-n junction gives information about the conduction behaviour of the diode, this is often measured using an analogue curve-tracer.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This sweeps the bias voltage in fine steps under tightly controlled laboratory conditions.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] For a SPAD, without photon arrivals or thermally generated carriers, the I-V characteristic is similar to the reverse characteristic of a standard semi-conductor diode, i.e. an almost total blockage of charge flow (current) over the junction other than a small leakage current (nano-amperes).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This condition can be described as an "off-branch" of the characteristic.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, when this experiment is conducted, a "flickering" effect and a second I-V characteristic can be observed beyond breakdown.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This occurs when the SPAD has experienced a triggering event (photon arrival or thermally generated carrier) during the voltage sweeps that are applied to the device.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The SPAD, during these sweeps, sustains an avalanche current which is described as the "on-branch" of the I-V characteristic.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As the curve tracer increases the magnitude of the bias voltage over time, there are times that the SPAD is triggered during the voltage sweep above breakdown.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In this case a transition occurs from the off-branch to the on-branch, with an appreciable current starting to flow.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This leads to the flickering of the I-V characteristic that is observed and was denoted by early researchers in the field as "bifurcation" (def: the division of something into two branches or parts).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] To detect single-photons successfully, the p-n junction must have very low levels of the internal generation and recombination processes.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] To reduce thermal generation, devices are often cooled, while phenomena such as tunnelling across the p-n junctions also need to be reduced through careful design of semi-conductor dopants and implant steps.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Finally, to reduce noise mechanisms being exacerbated by trapping centres within the p-n junction's band gap structure the diode needs to have a "clean" process free of erroneous dopants.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The simplest quenching circuit is commonly called passive quenching circuit and comprises a single resistor in series with the SPAD.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This experimental setup has been employed since the early studies on the avalanche breakdown in junctions.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The avalanche current self-quenches simply because it develops a voltage drop across a high-value ballast load RL (about 100 kΩ or more).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] After the quenching of the avalanche current, the SPAD bias slowly recovers to the operating bias, and therefore the detector is ready to be ignited again.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This circuit mode is therefore called passive quenching passive reset (PQPR), although an active circuit element can be used for reset forming a passive quench active reset (PQAR) circuit mode.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A detailed description of the quenching process is reported by Zappa et al.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A more advanced quenching, which was explored from the 1970s onwards, is a scheme called **active quenching**.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In this case a fast discriminator senses the steep onset of the avalanche current across a 50 Ω resistor (or integrated transistor) and provides a digital (CMOS, TTL, ECL, NIM) output pulse, synchronous with the photon arrival time.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The circuit then quickly reduces the bias voltage to below breakdown (active quenching), then relatively quickly returns bias to above the breakdown voltage ready to sense the next photon.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This mode is called active quench active reset (AQAR), however depending on circuit requirements, active quenching passive reset (AQPR) may be more suitable.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] AQAR circuits often allow lower dead times, and significantly reduced dead time variation.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The intensity of the input signal can be obtained by counting (photon counting) the number of output pulses within a measurement time period.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This is useful for applications such as low light imaging, PET scanning and fluorescence lifetime microscopy.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, while the avalanche recovery circuit is quenching the avalanche and restoring bias, the SPAD cannot detect further photon arrivals.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Any photons, (or dark counts or after-pulses), that reach the detector during this brief period are not counted.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As the number of photons increases such that the (statistical) time interval between photons gets within a factor of ten or so of the avalanche recovery time, missing counts become statistically significant and the count rate begins to depart from a linear relationship with detected light level.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] At this point the SPAD begins to saturate.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This can be harmful to the SPAD as it will be experiencing avalanche current nearly continuously.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In the passive case, saturation may lead to the count rate decreasing once the maximum is reached.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This is called paralysis, whereby a photon arriving as the SPAD is passively recharging, has a lower detection probability, but can extend the dead time.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] It is worth noting that passive quenching, while simpler to implement in terms of circuitry, incurs a 1/e reduction in maximum counting rates.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Besides photon-generated carriers, thermally-generated carriers (through generation-recombination processes within the semiconductor) can also fire the avalanche process.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Therefore, it is possible to observe output pulses when the SPAD is in complete darkness.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The resulting average number of counts per second is called *dark count rate* (DCR) and is the key parameter in defining the detector noise.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] It is worth noting that the reciprocal of the dark count rate defines the mean time that the SPAD remains biased above breakdown before being triggered by an undesired thermal generation.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Therefore, in order to work as a single-photon detector, the SPAD must be able to remain biased above breakdown for a sufficiently long time (e.g., a few milliseconds, corresponding to a count rate well under a thousand counts per second, cps).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] One other effect that can trigger an avalanche is known as afterpulsing.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] When an avalanche occurs, the PN junction is flooded with charge carriers and trap levels between the valence and conduction band become occupied to a degree that is much greater than that expected in a thermal-equilibrium distribution of charge carriers.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] After the SPAD has been quenched, there is some probability that a charge carrier in a trap level receives enough energy to free it from the trap and promote it to the conduction band, which triggers a new avalanche.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Thus, depending on the quality of the process and exact layers and implants that were used to fabricate the SPAD, a significant number of extra pulses can be developed from a single originating thermal or photo-generation event.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The degree of afterpulsing can be quantified by measuring the autocorrelation of the times of arrival between avalanches when a dark count measurement is set up.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Thermal generation produces Poissonian statistics with an impulse function autocorrelation, and afterpulsing produces non-Poissonian statistics.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The leading edge of a SPAD's avalanche breakdown is particularly useful for timing the arrival of photons.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This method is useful for 3D imaging, LIDAR and is used heavily in physical measurements relying on time-correlated single photon counting (TCSPC).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, to enable such functionality dedicated circuits such as time-to-digital converters (TDCs) and time-to-analogue (TAC) circuits are required.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The measurement of a photon's arrival is complicated by two general processes.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The first is the statistical fluctuation in the arrival time of the photon itself, which is a fundamental property of light.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The second is the statistical variation in the detection mechanism within the SPAD due to a) depth of photon absorption, b) diffusion time to the active p-n junction, c) the build up statistics of the avalanche and d) the jitter of the detection and timing circuitry.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] For a single SPAD, the ratio of its optically sensitive area, Aact, to its total area, Atot, is called the fill factor, FF = (Aact / Atot) × 100%.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As SPADs require a guard ring to prevent premature edge breakdown, the optical fill factor becomes a product of the diode shape and size with relation its guard ring.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] If the active area is large and the outer guard ring is thin, the device will have a high fill factor.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Fill factor is more applicable when we consider arrays of SPAD devices.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Here the diode active area may be small or commensurate with the guard ring's area.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Likewise, the fabrication process of the SPAD array may put constraints on the separation of one guard ring to another, i.e. the minimum separation of SPADs.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This leads to the situation where the area of the array becomes dominated by guard ring and separation regions rather than optically receptive p-n junctions.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The fill factor is made worse when circuitry must be included within the array as this adds further separation between optically receptive regions.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] One method to mitigate this issue is to increase the active area of each SPAD in the array such that guard rings and separation are no longer dominant, however for CMOS integrated SPADs the erroneous detections caused by dark counts increases as the diode size increases.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] One of the first methods to increase fill factors in arrays of circular SPADs was to offset the alignment of alternate rows such that the curve of one SPAD partially uses the area between the two SPADs on an adjacent row.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This was effective but complicated the routing and layout of the array.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] To address fill factor limitations within SPAD arrays formed of circular SPADs, other shapes are utilised as these are known to have higher maximum area values within a typically square pixel area and have higher packing ratios.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A square SPAD within a square pixel achieves the highest fill factor, however the sharp corners of this geometry are known to cause premature breakdown of the device, despite a guard ring and consequently produce SPADs with high dark count rates.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] To compromise, square SPADs with sufficiently rounded corners have been fabricated.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] These are termed Fermat shaped SPADs while the shape itself is a super-ellipse or a Lamé curve.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The degree "n" controls the curvature of the shape's corners.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Ideally, to optimise the shape of the diode for both low noise and a high fill factor, the shape's parameters should be free of these restrictions.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] To minimise the spacing between SPAD active areas, researchers have removed all active circuitry from the arrays and have also explored the use of NMOS only CMOS SPAD arrays to remove SPAD guard ring to PMOS n-well spacing rules.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This is of benefit but is limited by routing distances and congestion into the centre SPADs for larger arrays.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The concept has been extended to develop arrays that use clusters of SPADs in so-called mini-SiPM arrangements whereby a smaller array is provided with its active circuitry at one edge, allowing a second small array to be abutted on a different edge.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This reduced the routing difficulties by keeping the number of diodes in the cluster manageable and creating the required number of SPADs in total from collections of those clusters.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A significant jump in fill factor and array pixel pitch was achieved by sharing the deep n-well of the SPADs in CMOS processes, and more recently also sharing portions of the guard-ring structure.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This removed one of the major guard-ring to guard-ring separation rules and allowed the fill-factor to increase towards 60 or 70%.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The n-well and guard ring sharing idea has been crucial in efforts towards lowering pixel pitch and increasing the total number of diodes in the array.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Recently SPAD pitches have been reduced to 3.0 um and 2.2 um.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Porting a concept from photodiodes and APDs, researchers have also investigated the use of drift electric fields within the CMOS substrate to attract photo generated carriers towards a SPAD's active p-n junction.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] By doing so a large optical collection area can be achieved with a smaller SPAD region.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Another concept ported from CMOS image sensor technologies, is the exploration of stacked p-n junctions similar to Foveon sensors.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The idea being that higher-energy photons (blue) tend to be absorbed at a short absorption depth, i.e. near the silicon surface.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Red and infra-red photons (lower energy) travel deeper into the silicon.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] If there is a junction at that depth, red and IR sensitivity can be improved.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] With the advancement of 3D IC technologies, i.e. stacking of integrated circuits, the fill factor could be enhanced further by allowing the top die to be optimised for a high fill-factor SPAD array, and the lower die for readout circuits and signal processing.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As small dimension, high-speed processes for transistors may require different optimisations than optically sensitive diodes, 3D-ICs allow the layers to be separately optimised.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As with CMOS image sensors micro-lenses can be fabricated on the SPAD pixel array to focus light into the centre of the SPAD.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As with a single SPAD, this allows light to only hit the sensitive regions and avoid both the guard ring and any routing that is needed within the array.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This has also recently included Fresnel type lenses.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Within a single SPAD pixel, the sensitive region can be engineered as an optical metamaterial to create a wide variety of tailored absorption profiles.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The above fill-factor enhancement methods, mostly concentrating on SPAD geometry along with other advancements, have led SPAD arrays to recently push the 1 mega pixel barrier.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] While this lags CMOS image sensors (with pitches now below 0.8 um), this is a product of both the youth of the research field (with CMOS SPADs introduced in 2003) and the complications of high voltages, avalanche multiplication within the silicon and the required spacing rules.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] While both APDs and SPADs are semiconductor p-n junctions that are heavily reverse biased, the principle difference in their properties is derived from their different biasing points upon the reverse I-V characteristic, i.e. the reverse voltage applied to their junction.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] An APD, in comparison to a SPAD, is not biased above its breakdown voltage.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This is because the multiplication of charge carriers is known to occur prior to the breakdown of the device with this being utilised to achieve a stable gain that varies with the applied voltage.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] For optical detection applications, the resulting avalanche and subsequent current in its biasing circuit is linearly related to the optical signal intensity.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The APD is therefore useful to achieve moderate up-front amplification of low-intensity optical signals but is often combined with a trans-impedance amplifier (TIA) as the APD's output is a current rather than the voltage of a typical amplifier.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The resultant signal is a non-distorted, amplified version of the input, allowing for the measurement of complex processes that modulate the amplitude of the incident light.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The internal multiplication gain factors for APDs vary by application, however typical values are of the order of a few hundred.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The avalanche of carriers is not divergent in this operating region, while the avalanche present in SPADs quickly builds into a run-away (divergent) condition.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In comparison, SPADs operate at a bias voltage above the breakdown voltage.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This is such a highly unstable above-breakdown regime that a single photon or a single dark-current electron can trigger a significant avalanche of carriers.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The semiconductor p-n junction breaks down completely, and a significant current is developed.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] A single photon can trigger a current spike equivalent to billions of billions of electrons per second (with this being dependent on the physical size of the device and its bias voltage).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This allows subsequent electronic circuits to easily count such trigger events.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] As the device produces a trigger event, the concept of gain is not strictly compatible.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, as the photon detection efficiency (PDE) of SPADs varies with the reverse bias voltage, gain, in a general conceptual sense can be used to distinguish devices that are heavily biased and therefore highly sensitive in comparison to lightly biased and therefore of lower sensitivity.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] While APDs can amplify an input signal preserving any changes in amplitude, SPADs distort the signal into a series of trigger or pulse events.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The output can still be treated as proportional to the input signal intensity, however it is now transformed into the frequency of trigger events, i.e. pulse frequency modulation (PFM).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Pulses can be counted giving an indication of the input signal's optical intensity, while pulses can trigger timing circuits to provide accurate time-of-arrival measurements.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] One crucial issue present in APDs is multiplication noise induced by the statistical variation of the avalanche multiplication process.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This leads to a corresponding noise factor on the output amplified photo current.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Statistical variation in the avalanche is also present in SPAD devices, however due to the runaway process it is often manifest as timing jitter on the detection event.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The history and development of SPADs and APDs shares a number of important points with the development of solid-state technologies such as diodes and early p–n junction transistors (particularly war-efforts at Bell Labs).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] John Townsend in 1901 and 1903 investigated the ionisation of trace gases within vacuum tubes, finding that as the electric potential increased, gaseous atoms and molecules could become ionised by the kinetic energy of free electrons accelerated though the electric field.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The new liberated electrons were then themselves accelerated by the field, producing new ionisations once their kinetic energy has reached sufficient levels.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This theory was later instrumental in the development of the thyratron and the Geiger-Mueller tube.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] The Townsend discharge was also instrumental as a base theory for electron multiplication phenomena, (both DC and AC), within both silicon and germanium.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] However, the major advances in early discovery and utilisation of the avalanche gain mechanism were a product of the study of Zener breakdown, related (avalanche) breakdown mechanisms and structural defects in early silicon and germanium transistor and p–n junction devices.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] These defects were called 'microplasmas' and are critical in the history of APDs and SPADs.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Likewise investigation of the light detection properties of p–n junctions is crucial, especially the early 1940s findings of Russel Ohl.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Light detection in semiconductors and solids through the internal photoelectric effect is older with Foster Nix pointing to the work of Gudden and Pohl in the 1920s, who use the phrase primary and secondary to distinguish the internal and external photoelectric effects respectively.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In the 1950s and 1960s, significant effort was made to reduce the number of microplasma breakdown and noise sources, with artificial microplasmas being fabricated for study.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] It became clear that the avalanche mechanism could be useful for signal amplification within the diode itself, as both light and alpha particles were used for the study of these devices and breakdown mechanisms.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] In the early 2000s, SPADs have been implemented within CMOS processes.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] This has radically increased their performance (dark count rate, jitter, array pixel pitch, etc.), and has leveraged analog and digital circuits that can be implemented alongside these devices.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Such devices are now reaching optical fill factors of >70%, with >1024 SPADs, with DCRs < 10 Hz, jitter values in the 50ps region, and dead times of 1-2ns.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Recent devices leverage 3D-IC technologies such as through-silicon-vias (TSVs) to present a high-fill-factor SPAD optimised top CMOS layer (90 nm or 65 nm node) with a dedicated signal processing and readout CMOS layer (45 nm node).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/single-photon-avalanche-diode] Significant advancements in the noise terms for SPADs have been obtained by silicon process modelling tools such as TCAD, where guard rings, junction depths and device structures and shapes can be optimised prior to validation by experimental SPAD structures.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In electronics, one of the earliest devices using the principle are ultrasonic distance-measuring devices, which emit an ultrasonic pulse and are able to measure the distance to a solid object based on the time taken for the wave to bounce back to the emitter.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The ToF method is also used to estimate the electron mobility.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Originally, it was designed for measurement of low-conductive thin films, later adjusted for common semiconductors.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] This experimental technique is used for metal-dielectric-metal structures as well as organic field-effect transistors.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The excess charges are generated by application of the laser or voltage pulse.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] For magnetic resonance angiography (MRA), ToF is a major underlying method.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In this method, blood entering the imaged area is not yet saturated, giving it a much higher signal when using short echo time and flow compensation.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] It can be used in the detection of aneurysm, stenosis or dissection.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In time-of-flight mass spectrometry, ions are accelerated by an electrical field to the same kinetic energy with the velocity of the ion depending on the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Thus the time-of-flight is used to measure velocity, from which the mass-to-charge ratio can be determined.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The time-of-flight of electrons is used to measure their kinetic energy.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In near-infrared spectroscopy, the ToF method is used to measure the media-dependent optical pathlength over a range of optical wavelengths, from which composition and properties of the media can be analyzed.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In ultrasonic flow meter measurement, ToF is used to measure speed of signal propagation upstream and downstream of flow of a media, in order to estimate total flow velocity.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] This measurement is made in a collinear direction with the flow.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In optical interferometry, the pathlength difference between sample and reference arms can be measured by ToF methods, such as frequency modulation followed by phase shift measurement or cross correlation of signals.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Such methods are used in laser radar and laser tracker systems for medium-long range distance measurement.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In neutron time-of-flight scattering, a pulsed monochromatic neutron beam is scattered by a sample.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The energy spectrum of the scattered neutrons is measured via time of flight.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In kinematics, ToF is the duration in which a projectile is traveling through the air.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The time-of-flight principle can be applied for mass spectrometry.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Ions are accelerated by an electric field of known strength.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] This acceleration results in an ion having the same kinetic energy as any other ion that has the same charge.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The velocity of the ion depends on the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The time that it subsequently takes for the particle to reach a detector at a known distance is measured.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] This time will depend on the mass-to-charge ratio of the particle (heavier particles reach lower speeds).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] From this time and the known experimental parameters one can find the mass-to-charge ratio of the ion.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The elapsed time from the instant a particle leaves a source to the instant it reaches a detector.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] An ultrasonic flow meter measures the velocity of a liquid or gas through a pipe using acoustic sensors.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] This has some advantages over other measurement techniques.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The results are slightly affected by temperature, density or conductivity.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Maintenance is inexpensive because there are no moving parts.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Ultrasonic flow meters come in three different types: transmission (contrapropagating transit time) flowmeters, reflection (Doppler) flowmeters, and open-channel flowmeters.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Transit time flowmeters work by measuring the time difference between an ultrasonic pulse sent in the flow direction and an ultrasound pulse sent opposite the flow direction.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Doppler flowmeters measure the doppler shift resulting in reflecting an ultrasonic beam off either small particles in the fluid, air bubbles in the fluid, or the flowing fluid's turbulence.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Open channel flow meters measure upstream levels in front of flumes or weirs.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Optical time-of-flight sensors consist of two light beams projected into the fluid whose detection is either interrupted or instigated by the passage of small particles (which are assumed to be following the flow).
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] This is not dissimilar from the optical beams used as safety devices in motorized garage doors or as triggers in alarm systems.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The speed of the particles is calculated by knowing the spacing between the two beams.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] If there is only one detector, then the time difference can be measured via autocorrelation.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] If there are two detectors, one for each beam, then direction can also be known.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Since the location of the beams is relatively easy to determine, the precision of the measurement depends primarily on how small the setup can be made.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] If the beams are too far apart, the flow could change substantially between them, thus the measurement becomes an average over that space.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Moreover, multiple particles could reside between them at any given time, and this would corrupt the signal since the particles are indistinguishable.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] For such a sensor to provide valid data, it must be small relative to the scale of the flow and the seeding density.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] MOEMS approaches yield extremely small packages, making such sensors applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Usually the time-of-flight tube used in mass spectrometry is praised for simplicity, but for precision measurements of charged low energy particles the electric and the magnetic field in the tube has to be controlled within 10 mV and 1 nT respectively.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The work function homogeneity of the tube can be controlled by a Kelvin probe.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The magnetic field can be measured by a fluxgate compass.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] High frequencies are passively shielded and damped by radar absorbent material.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] To generate arbitrary low frequencies field the screen is parted into plates (overlapping and connected by capacitors) with bias voltage on each plate and a bias current on coil behind plate whose flux is closed by an outer core.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] In this way the tube can be configured to act as a weak achromatic quadrupole lens with an aperture with a grid and a delay line detector in the diffraction plane to do angle resolved measurements.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Changing the field the angle of the field of view can be changed and a deflecting bias can be superimposed to scan through all angles.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] When no delay line detector is used focusing the ions onto a detector can be accomplished through the use of two or three einzel lenses placed in the vacuum tube located between the ion source and the detector.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The sample should be immersed into the tube with holes and apertures for and against stray light to do magnetic experiments and to control the electrons from their start.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Laser-based time-of-flight cameras are part of a broader class of scannerless LIDAR, in which the entire scene is captured with each laser pulse, as opposed to point-by-point with a laser beam such as in scanning LIDAR systems.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] Time-of-flight camera products for civil applications began to emerge around 2000, as the semiconductor processes allowed the production of components fast enough for such devices.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The systems cover ranges of a few centimeters up to several kilometers.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] A time-of-flight (TOF) detector is a particle detector which can discriminate between a lighter and a heavier elementary particle of same momentum using their time of flight between two scintillators.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The first of the scintillators activates a clock upon being hit while the other stops the clock upon being hit.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] where L is the distance between the scintillators.
[src:time-of-flight-sensors/time-of-flight] The approximation is in the relativistic limit at momentum p and c denotes the speed of light in vacuum.
